<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF90FFC164B3F96E5BE6FF65" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164B3F96E587EFCBD" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" box="[151,351,362,388]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">DESCRIPTION:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3F98B58F7FC91" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" box="[199,470,398,424]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC164E3F98B5875FC91" box="[199,340,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Wing length</emphasis>
: ±6.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3F9B75A5DFCC9" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC164E3F9B75827FCF5" box="[199,262,435,460]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF90FFC16533F9B65853FCF5" box="[279,370,434,460]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,1139,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-312@8.[151,1436,1132,1855]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Anopheles paludis: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521620" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521620/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Fig. 7a</figureCitation>
): Sector, subcostal and preapical pale spots prominent; apical pale fringe spot opposite R 
<subScript id="17A034EBFF90FFC16488F9EC5994FCCF" attach="left" box="[172,181,488,502]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">3</subScript>
; pale fringe spot present opposite CuA 
<subScript id="17A034EBFF90FFC166B3F9EC5B81FCCF" attach="left" box="[663,672,488,502]" fontSize="6" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">2</subScript>
, sometimes faint.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3F9FE5A2EFF2D" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" box="[199,783,506,532]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC164E3F9FE58B1FF2D" box="[199,400,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Maxillary palpus</emphasis>
: Shaggy, with four pale bands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3FA1B5BE6FF65" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC164E3FA1B5820FF01" box="[199,257,543,568]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF90FFC16531FA1A5854FF00" box="[277,373,542,569]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,1139,1848]" captionTargetId="figure-312@8.[151,1436,1132,1855]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Anopheles paludis: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521620" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521620/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Fig. 7b</figureCitation>
): Hindleg with apex of tibia narrowly pale; base of hindtarsomere 1 dark, as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF90FFC16156FA1A583AFF65" authorityName="Donitz" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrosus">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16156FA1A583AFF65" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">An. tenebrosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; hindtarsomeres 3–5 entirely pale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF90FFC164E3FA6258E8FED1" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3FA625D02FF9D" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">LARVAL HABITAT: Natural collections of clear water with aquatic and semi-aquatic vegetation, such as swamps, ponds, backwaters of streams, springs, ditches and rice fields.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF90FFC164E3FAAA58E8FED1" blockId="8.[151,1437,362,1108]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">
ADULT BIOLOGY: Mainly zoophilic but females feed on humans in some areas. In certain areas of the 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF90FFC1616AFAAA5CBDFFF1" box="[1358,1436,686,712]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Congo</collectingCountry>
basin, the species is regularly captured indoors, and females with 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF90FFC16789FAD75D6CFFD5" box="[941,1101,722,748]" family="Plasmodiidae" genus="Plasmodium" kingdom="Chromista" order="Eucoccidiida" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" phylum="Miozoa" rank="species" species="falciparum">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16789FAD75D6CFFD5" box="[941,1101,722,748]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">P. falciparum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
salivary gland infections as high as 10% have been reported (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC1660CFAF25A77FE29" author="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B." box="[552,854,758,784]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="1 - 343" refId="ref8483" refString="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B. (1968) The Anophelinae of Africa south of the Sahara (Ethiopian Zoogeographical Region). Publications of the South African Institute for Medical Research, 54, 1 - 343." type="journal article" year="1968">Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC16746FAF25D4CFE29" author="Gillies, M. T. &amp; Coetzee, M." box="[866,1133,758,784]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="1 - 143" refId="ref8437" refString="Gillies, M. T. &amp; Coetzee, M. (1987) A supplement to the Anophelinae of Africa south of the Sahara (Afrotropical Region). Publications of the South African Institute for Medical Research, 55, 1 - 143." type="journal article" year="1987">Gillies &amp; Coetzee 1987</bibRefCitation>
). In the Bandungu region of the 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF90FFC164C4FB1E583EFE0D" box="[224,287,794,820]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">DRC</collectingCountry>
, a 6.2% sporozoite rate was recorded by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC166D3FB1E5D03FE0D" author="Karch, S. &amp; Mouchet, J." box="[759,1058,794,820]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="388 - 389" refId="ref9421" refString="Karch, S. &amp; Mouchet, J. (1992) Anopheles paludis: vecteur important du paludisme au Zaire. Bulletin de la Societe de Pathologie Exotique, 85 (5), 388 - 389." type="journal article" year="1992">Karch &amp; Mouchet (1992)</bibRefCitation>
, but no infections were recorded in the capital of Kinshasa (Karch 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16610FB3B5B53FE61" box="[564,626,830,856]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">et al.</emphasis>
1992; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC166EEFB3A5A7FFE61" author="Coene, J." box="[714,862,830,856]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="127 - 137" refId="ref7528" refString="Coene, J. (1993) Malaria in urban and rural Kinshasa: the entomological input. Medical and Veterinary Entomology, 7, 127 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2915.1993. tb 00665. x" type="journal article" year="1993">Coene 1993</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF90FFC167BCFB3A5D37FE61" box="[920,1046,830,856]" name="Cameroon" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, there are several reports of 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF90FFC16150FB3A59CFFE45" authorityName="Theobald" authorityYear="1900" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paludis">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16150FB3A59CFFE45" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">An. paludis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
infected with parasites: 0.15% (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC16655FB665A92FE44" author="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B." box="[625,947,866,893]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="1 - 343" refId="ref8483" refString="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B. (1968) The Anophelinae of Africa south of the Sahara (Ethiopian Zoogeographical Region). Publications of the South African Institute for Medical Research, 54, 1 - 343." type="journal article" year="1968">Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968</bibRefCitation>
), 1.12% (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC16002FB665CAEFE44" author="Antonio-Nkondjio, C. &amp; Kerah, C. H. &amp; Simard, F. &amp; Awono-Ambene, P. &amp; Chouaibou, M. &amp; Tchuinkam, T. &amp; Fontenille, D." box="[1062,1423,866,893]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="1215 - 1221" refId="ref6648" refString="Antonio-Nkondjio, C., Kerah, C. H., Simard, F., Awono-Ambene, P., Chouaibou, M., Tchuinkam, T. &amp; Fontenille, D. (2006) Complexity of the malaria vectorial system in Cameroon: contribution of secondary vectors to malaria transmission. Journal of Medical Entomology, 43 (6), 1215 - 1221. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jmedent / 43.6.1215" type="journal article" year="2006">
Antonio-Nkondjio 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC1612FFB675C66FE45" box="[1291,1351,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
), 7.1% (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC164C0FB8258E2FE99" author="Bigoga, J. D. &amp; Nanfack, F. M. &amp; Awono-Ambene, P. H. &amp; Patchoke, S. &amp; Atangana, J. &amp; Otia, V. S. &amp; Fondjo, E. &amp; Moyou, R. S. &amp; Leke, R. G." box="[228,451,902,928]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="197" refId="ref7083" refString="Bigoga, J. D., Nanfack, F. M., Awono-Ambene, P. H., Patchoke, S., Atangana, J., Otia, V. S., Fondjo, E., Moyou, R. S. &amp; Leke, R. G. (2012) Seasonal prevalence of malaria vectors and entomological inoculation rates in the rubber cultivated area of Niete, South Region of Cameroon. Parasites &amp; Vectors, 5, 197. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / 1756 - 3305 - 5 - 197" type="journal article" year="2012">
Bigoga 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16566FB83585CFE99" box="[322,381,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
), 3.4% (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC16600FB825BD5FE99" author="Tabue, R. N. &amp; Awono-Ambene, P. &amp; Etang, J. &amp; Atangana, J. &amp; Antonio-Nkondjio, C. &amp; Toto, J. C. &amp; Patchoke, S. &amp; Leke, R. G. &amp; Fondjo, E. &amp; Mnzava, A. P. &amp; Knox, T. B. &amp; Tougordi, A. &amp; Donnelly, M. J. &amp; Bigoga, J. D." box="[548,756,902,928]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="22" refId="ref11429" refString="Tabue, R. N., Awono-Ambene, P., Etang, J., Atangana, J., Antonio-Nkondjio, C., Toto, J. C., Patchoke, S., Leke, R. G., Fondjo, E., Mnzava, A. P., Knox, T. B., Tougordi, A., Donnelly, M. J. &amp; Bigoga, J. D. (2017) Role of Anopheles (Cellia) rufipes (Gough, 1910) and other local anophelines in human malaria transmission in the northern savannah of Cameroon: a cross-sectional survey. Parasites &amp; Vectors, 10, 22. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 016 - 1933 - 3" type="journal article" year="2017">
Tabue 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC16651FB835B91FE99" box="[629,688,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
) and 0.7% (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF90FFC167A6FB825D43FE99" author="Bamou, R. &amp; Mbakop, L. R. &amp; Kopya, E. &amp; Ndo, C. &amp; Awono-Ambene, P. &amp; Tchuinkam, T. &amp; Rono, M. K. &amp; Mwangangi, J. &amp; Nkondjio, C." box="[898,1122,902,928]" pageId="8" pageNumber="190" pagination="464" refId="ref6986" refString="Bamou, R., Mbakop, L. R., Kopya, E., Ndo, C., Awono-Ambene, P., Tchuinkam, T., Rono, M. K., Mwangangi, J. &amp; Antonio- Nkondjio, C. (2018) Changes in malaria vector bionomics and transmission patterns in the equatorial forest region of Cameroon between 2000 and 2017. Parasites &amp; Vectors, 11, 464. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 018 - 3049 - 4" type="journal article" year="2018">
Bamou 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF90FFC167C4FB835D3AFE99" box="[992,1051,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF90FFC160B0FB825DC0FE99" box="[1172,1249,902,928]" name="Gabon" pageId="8" pageNumber="190">Gabon</collectingCountry>
, 
